text: ANALYSES BY STUDENT SUBGROUP OF SCHOOL
label: HH1

text: Historically, on State assessments the average performance of Black, Hispanic, and Native American
label: BODY

text: students has been lower than that of White and Asian students. Similarly, students from low-income
label: BODY

text: families have not performed as well as those from higher income families.  A high priority of the Board of
label: BODY

text: Regents is to eliminate these gaps in student performance. In addition, Title 1 of the federal Elementary
label: BODY

text: and Secondary Education Act includes explicit requirements “to ensure that students served by Title 1 are
label: BODY

text: given the same opportunity to achieve to high standards and are held to the same high expectations as
label: BODY

text: all students in each State.” Beginning with this report card, New York State will report performance data
label: BODY

text: by gender, disability status, racial/ethnic group, English proficiency status, migrant status, and income
label: BODY

text: level.  District reports do not show high school performance data by gender, racial/ethnic group, migrant
label: BODY

text: status, or income level because data were available only from high schools that received Title 1 funding.
label: BODY

text: The purpose of the analyses on the following pages is to determine if students who perform below the
label: BODY

text: standards in this district tend to fall into particular groups, such as minority students, English language
label: BODY

text: learners, or economically disadvantaged students. If these analyses provide evidence that students in
label: BODY

text: one of the groups achieve at a lower level than other students, the district and community should examine
label: BODY

text: the reasons for this lower performance and make necessary changes in curriculum, instruction and
label: BODY

text: student support services to remedy these performance gaps.
label: BODY

text: It is important that programmatic changes be based on valid and reliable data. If a district does not have
label: BODY

text: 20 students in a group in a given year, the district should evaluate results for students in this group over a
label: BODY

text: period of years to make programmatic decisions. To protect the privacy of students, the Department’s
label: BODY

text: policy is never to publish data for groups with fewer than five students, nor to publish data that would
label: BODY

text: allow readers to easily determine the performance of a group smaller than five. If the number of students
label: BODY

text: in small group racial/ethnic groups exceeds four, the aggregate performance of students in these groups
label: BODY

text: is shown in the last row (Small Group Totals) of Results by Race/Ethnicity.

text: General-education students who first entered ninth grade in 1997 must score 55 or higher on Regents
label: BODY

text: English and mathematics examinations to graduate. During the phase-in of the Regents examination
label: BODY

text: graduation requirements, all students (with local Board approval) may qualify for a local diploma by
label: BODY

text: earning a score of 55-64 on the required Regents examinations; a score of 65 or higher is required for a
label: BODY

text: Regents diploma. Students with disabilities and certain Section 504 students may qualify for a local
label: BODY
